                    <marginalia_text>
                        Mirum, ac horrendum facinus patris in filiam. pra[e]stitisset Appio, non irritasse tam violentum militem. famosum argumentum stupenda[e] 
                        Comicotragoedia[e]. Huc illa Aristotelis memorabilia, de iactatis, mutatisq[ue] Rebusp[ublicis] foeminarum causa. Et auguste honoranda Alexandri, 
                        Scipionisq[ue] excellentissima Temperantia; in tanto feruore a[e]tatis, roboris, victoria[e]. Hoc Agebant singulares viri; nugas spernebant.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Appius Claudius Crassus"/>
                    <person name="Aristotle"/>
                    <person name="Alexander the Great"/>
                    <person name="Scipio Africanus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>An extraordinary and dreadful deed of a father against his daughter. It would have been best for Appius not to provoke such a violent soldier. 
                It is a notorious subject of astonishing tragicomedy. On this [see] those memorable remarks of Aristotle about turbulence and change in states because 
                of women. Also one should respectfully honour the superior restraint of Alexander and Scipio in such great passion of youth, power and victory. 
                These remarkable men paid attention to this, they paid no attention to frivolities.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
